AFTER DRIVER HOOKED UP HOSES AND RECEIVED THE OK TO UNLOAD, HE OPENED THE VALVES AND STARTED PRODUCT PUMP TO TRANSFER PRODUCT. PUMP STARTED TO MAKE A STRAINING NOISE. DRIVER SHUT DOWN AND DISCOVERED CONSIGNEE'S HOSE END BLEW OFF HOSE. UNLOADER GOT SPLASHED WITH SPRAY. DRIVER HELPED HIM TO SHOWER TO GET CLEANED OFF. IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THEIR AUTOMATIC HIGH LEVEL VALVE MALFUNCTIONED AND CLOSED WHICH CAUSED PRESSURE TO BUILD UP IN THEIR HOSE. CONSIGNEE CLEANED AREA AND MADE REPAIRS.

AFTER DELIVERY OF PRODUCT WAS COMPLETE AND DISCHARGE AND VAPOR LINES WERE PURGED WITH NITROGEN. THE LIQUID LINE HAD A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRESSURE. DRIVER NOTIFIED UNLOADING SUPERVISOR. GAUGE WAS CHECKED ON SCRUBBER TANK AND IT REVEALED 0. GAUGE ON TRAILER STATED 4 LBS. DRIVER SHUT VALVES OFF ON PURGE LINE AND DISCONNECTED NITROGEN HOSE. DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TO CRACK  PURGE VALVE OPEN TO CHECK FOR PRESSURE BEFORE DISCONNECTING DISCHARGE AND VAPORS HOSES. PRODUCT SPRAYED OUT OF PURGE VALVE. DRIVER CLOSED VALVE AND APPLIED STEAM TO THE VALVE AREA TO NEUTRALIZE RELEASE. UNLOADING SUPERVISOR RECHECKED LINES AND VALVES. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THEIR 3-WAY VALVE WAS FROZEN AND DIDN'T RELEASE PRESSURE IN LINES. VALVE WAS STEAMED OPEN AND PRESSURE WAS RELEASED IN LINE AND DRIVER MADE HIS DISCONNECT. WE WERE INFORMED THAT A PERSON IN AREA MIGHT OF COME IN CONTACT WITH THE VAPOR. HE WAS TAKEN TO FIRST AID AND RELEASED.

column168: THE DRIVER NOTICED A FOG OR SMOKE IN THE HEADLIGHT OF A CAR THAT HE WAS PASSING. THE DRIVER THOUGHT THAT ONE OF THE TRAILER BRAKES WAS LOCKED UP. THE DRIVER PULLED OFF TO THE SIDE OF I-65 TO INSPECT. UPON INSPECTION, HE FOUND A LIQUID RUNNING OUT OF THE VAN TRAILER THAT HE WAS PULLING. THE DRIVER PULLED HIS RECOVERY DRUM OUT OF ITS HOLDER AND SLIDE IT UNDER THE TRAILER TO CATCH THE LIQUID THAT WAS RUNNING OUT OF  A PORTABLE TANK ON THE VAN TRAILER. THE DRIVER GOT ON HIS CB RADIO AND REQUESTED HELP. THE INDIANA STATE POLICE TELEPHONED OUR HENDERSON, KENTUCKY FACILITY AND TOLD OUR SECURITY GUARD ABOUT THE PROBLEM. WE SENT OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM AND HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE TO HANDLE THE SPILL AND CLEAN UP. THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND THE SPILL AREA WAS CLEANED UP. AFTER INVESTIGATION OF THE PORTABLE THE CONCLUSION WAS THAT THE PIPE NIPPLE THAT THREADS INTO THE TANK AND OUTLET VALVE FAILED DUE TO BEING STRUCK BY A FORK ON A FORKLIFT TRUCK AND THEN FROM THE VIBRATION OF THE ROAD.

CLARK FREIGHT TRUCKING COMPANY ARRIVED AT SEA-LAND TERMINAL TO DELIVER PORTABLE TANK CHI39681 AS AN EXPORT SHIPMENT.  UPON INSPECTION, A MECHANIC SAW PRODUCT LEAKING FROM ALL THREE SEAM UNDER THE TANK.  THE TANK WAS ISOLATED AND THREE BUCKETS WERE PLACED UNDER EACH LEAKING SEAM.  THE PORT OF HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT TEMPORARILY PATCHED THE SEAL TO PREVENT PRODUCT FROM LEAKING ONTO THE GROUND SO THE TANK COULD BE TAKEN TO THE ISOLATED RAILHEAD. THE PORT OF HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT CLEANED UP THE PRODUCT THAT HAD SPILLED ONTO THE ASPHALT/CONCRETE (LESS THAN ONE GALLON HAD SPILLED). WHILED THEY WERE HANDLING IMMEDIATE RESPONSE, PAT PARRISH NOTIFIED HELEN KERLEY AT T. KERLEY. KERLEY'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED (JAMIE SPAIN SHEPPARD). A SECOND TANK DCI10440106 WAS PROVIDED TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT FROM DCIU440100. THE SEALS WERE TEMPORARILY PATCHED ALLOWING THE TANK TO BE DRAYED BACK OVER TO KERLEY'S PLANT. KERLEY ASSOCIATES HANDLED TRANSFER AND SET UP CLARK FREIGHT TO DRAY BOTH TO THE PLANT.  BOTH TANKS LEFT THE FACILITY BEFORE 1900.  APPROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS SPILLED INTO THE BUCKETS.  KERLEY REPRESENTATIVE TOOK CONTAMINATED EQUIPMENT, SUPPLIES AND PRODUCT.  KERLEY IS HANDLING DISPOSAL.  PAT PARRISH MADE NOTIFICATIONS TO HELEN KERLEY AT APPROXIMATELY 2:00 P.M., THE PORT OF HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT AT APPROXIMATELY 1:50 PM., THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AT APPROXIMATELY 2:35 P.M. (REPORT #424058), AND THE TNRCC STEVE HAMON AT APPROXIMATELY 2:50 P.M.  PAT WAS CONTACTED BY U.S. COAST GUARD W. MCCARSON AND OFFICER RAY BALL.  PETTY OFFICER RAY BALL CAME TO THE FACILITY TO INSPECT TANK AND OBSERVE TANK HANDLING OPERATIONS. SHIPPING PAPERWORK WAS FAXED TO USCG PETTY OFFICER RAY BALL AS REQUESTED.

SAFEWAY TRANSPORTATION WAS DELIVERING TO SEA-LAND TERMINAL A PORTABLE TANK, FITU524002 FOR EXPORTATION ON BOOKING CHI290056, AT APPROXIMATELY 15l30.  DURING THE INSPECTION OF THE TANK, AN ODOR WAS DISCOVERED COMING FROM THE TANK. THE FOREMAN NOTIFIED PAT PARRISH AND REQUESTED THE TANK BE CHECKED FOR LEAKS. THE TRUCK WAS ISOLATED.  PAT COULD NOT SEE ANY PRODUCT OR VAPORS.  SHE NOTIFIED PORT OF HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT TO COME CHECK THE TANK FOR POSSIBLE LEAK.  IT COULD NOT BE DETERMINED AT THAT MOMENT IF A PRODUCT WAS LEAKING OR PRODUCT HAD SPILLED ON THE SHELL AND NEEDED CLEANING.  SGT. ELDER WITH FIRE DEPARTMENT ADVISED TO CALL THE SHIPPER AND ASKED THEM TO COME TO THE FACILITY TO CHECK THE TANK.  WE COULD NOT FIND THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR BUT KNEW IT NEEDED TO BE VERIFIED.  SINCE NO APPARENT MAJOR LEAK EXISTED THE TANK WAS MOVED TO ISOLATION AREA ON BERTH 1.  PAT PARRISH NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER FLEXITANK, ROSENDO RIOS.  ROSENDO NOTIFIED THEIR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM TO RESPOND. WHILE WAITING FOR RESENDO TO ADVISE ETA ON RESPONSE TEAM, THE POH FIRE DEPARTMENT CALLED SAYING THE TANK WAS ACTUALLY LEAKING.  FIRST THOUGHT FROM THE SEAL OR BLOWOUT PLUG ON REAR VALVE.  FLEXITANK REPRESENTATIVE CONTACTED SGT. ELDER TO DISCUSS POSSIBLE ACTION NEEDED.  PAT PARRISH WITH SEA-LAND THEN BEGAN MAKING NOTIFICATIONS TO REQUIRED AGENCIES:  NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER CHRIS SAVAGE, REPORT NUMBER 424253, TIME 17:00.  I ADVISED THE SITUATION WAS UNDER CONTROL, NO MAJOR RELEASE.  LESS THAN 1/4 CUP.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ADVISED WINDS BLOWING APPROX 15 KNOTS FROM SOUTHEAST, VAPOR WAS DISSIPATING.  PAT THEN TRIED TO NOTIFY TNRCC, STEVE HAMN BY PAGER. IN THE MEANTIME, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT CALLED BACK ADVISING THE LEAK HAD STOPPED, APPROX 17:15.  THE LEADER VALVE IN THE WELL WAS NOT COVERED.  THEY PUT THE PLUG OVER THE VALVE WHICH IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE LEAK.  I THEN CALLED FLEXITANK-ROSENDO TO ADVISED THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. REPRESENTATIVES FROM SAFEWAY TRANSPORTATION AND C-CAM STILL RESPONDED TO CHECK OUT THE TANK.  I THEN CALLED CHRIS SAVAGE AT NRC AND ADVISED THE LEAK HAD STOPPED.  I ASKED WHO HE HAD NOTIFIED.  HE REPLIED HE HAD NOTIFIED EPA REGION 6.  I REQUESTED HE CONTACT THEM AND ADVISE LEAK HAD BEEN REPAIRED. REPRESENTATIVE FROM SAFEWAY-HENRY WILSON AND C-CAM.  RUSSELL HARRISON INSPECTED THE TANK AND ADVISED TANK WAS SEA WORTHY.  TANK WAS ACCEPTED FOR ON CARRIAGE TO PUERTO RICO.  NO CLEAN UP WAS NECESSARY BECAUSE THE VAPORS HAD DISSIPATED.  I REQUESTED SAFEWAY AND C-CAM TO REVIEW THEIR PROCEDURES TO ENSURE PLUGS ARE IN PLACE, VALVES ARE CLOSED.  ALSO ASKED THAT THEY REVIEW A WAY TO KEEP PRODUCTS FROM SPILLING INTO THE WELL WHEN REMOVING THE HOSE WHEN LOADING. ODORS LINGER FOR SEVERAL HOURS WHEN A MINUTE AMOUNT DROPS FROM THE HOSES DURING LOADING.

column168: WE DELIVERED 60-15 GALLON CBYS. OF SULFURIC ACID TO NEWARK, NJ. AFTER OFF LOADING 26 CBYS. OUR DRIVER NOTICED A CARBOY ON THE VAN WHICH WAS LEAKING.  HE DID NOT OFFLOAD IT AND TURNED IT UPSIDE DOWN TO STOP THE LEAK AND STRAPPED IT TO THE VAN WALL SEGREGATING IT. 1 QUART OF ACID SPILLED ON THE FLOOR OF THE VAN SO HE DID NOT OFFLOAD THE REST OF THE SHIPMENT.  THE VAN WAS WASHED OUT AND THE EFFLUENT ADDED BACK TO THE PROCESS.  THE NEW 15 GALLON CARBOY FAILED DURING TRANSPORT.  EIGHT CARBOYS ARE SHRINKWRAPPED TOGETHER AND PLACED ON A PALLET.  TWO PALLETS A  4X4 EACH ARE PLACED SIDE BY SIDE IN THE VAN.  DURING SHIPMENT THE GROUP OF EIGHT CARBOYS SLIPPED PARTIALLY IN BETWEEN THE PALLETS AND A SHARP EDGE OF A NEW PALLET WORE A GROOVE INTO THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF THE CARBOYS WHICH BECAME PARTIALLY WEDGED BETWEEN THE PALLETS.  THE GROVE CUT DEEP ENOUGH TO CAUSE THE SLIGHT LEAK.  WE ARE NOW STRAPPING PALLET LOADS TO THE SIDE OF OUR TRAILER TO PREVENT SLIPPAGE .  EACH SET OF SHRINK WRAPPED CARBOYS ARE SEPARATELY STRAPPED TO THE E-TRACK OF THE VAN.
FREIGHT WAS REFUSED BY CUSTOMER DUE TO PAIL LEAKING.  THE PAIL WAS DENTED.  THE DAMAGED PAIL WAS RECOUPED AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

column168: LOOSE PACKING GLAND UTLX 80529, FEBRUARY 8, 1998, PITTSBURGH DIVISION. AT APPROXIMATELY 0100 HOURS, SATURDAY, FEBRUARY 8, 1998, A CONRAIL CREW NOTED AN ODOR EMANATING FROM TANK CAR UTLX 80529 CONTAINING THE RESIDUE OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, LIQUEFIED. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. THE AREA WAS ISOLATED. AT APPROXIMATELY 0302 HOURS, CONRAIL'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SERVICE MANAGER ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE CAR AND DETERMINED THAT A VAPOR LEAK WAS NOTED BETWEEN THE "SLIP TUBE" AND THE PACKING GLAND. THE PACKING GLAND HAD TWO (2) GOUGES IN IT AT ITS TOP. THESE APPEARED TO BE "CHISELED" IN THE PACKING GLAND. THE "SLIP TUBE" WAS EASILY ROTATED BY HAND. THIS WAS DUE TO THE PACKING GLAND NOT BEING SUFFICIENTLY TIGHT TO SECURE THIS FITTING AND RENDER ITS VAPOR TIGHT. AT APPROXIMATELY 0330 HOURS, REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE SHIPPER, DYNO NOBEL ARRIVED AT THE SITE. REPAIRS WERE MADE BY CONRAIL'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SERVICE MANAGER AND DYNO NOBEL REPRESENTATIVES WHO USED AN EIGHT INCH PIPE WRENCH TO TIGHTEN THE PACKING GLAND. AT APPROXIMATELY 0410 HOURS, LEAK STOPPED.

WE HAD TWO OF OUR TRUCKS RUNNING TOGETHER.  THE HAD BEEN TO WICHITA, KS AND WERE RETURNING TO PRYOR, OK.  THE TWO TRUCKS WERE TRAVELING EAST ON I-412.  THEY HAD BEEN RUNNING IN PATCHY FOG.  THEY HAD RUN INTO ONE PATCH OF FOG THAT WAS VERY THICK AND DID NOT REALIZE THEY WERE GOING TO PASS THROUGH A TOLL. BOOTH.  BECAUSE OF THE FOG THEY WERE NOT ABLE TO SEE ANY OF THE WARNING SIGNS.  THE FIRST TRUCK REALIZED THEY WERE AT A TOLL BOOTH ONLY WHEN A CAR THAT HAD JUST PAST HIM AND GOT BACK IN FRONT OF HIM APPLIED THEIR BRAKES.  THE SECOND TRUCK NEVER SAW ANYTHING AND HIT THE REAR OF THE FIRST TRUCK. THE TANK THAT WAS HIT, STAYED INTACT BUT SOME OF THE PIPING LEAKED.

THERE WERE NO INJURIES REPORTED, AND THE SUBSTANCE WAS CLEANED UP BY THE DG SPILL CLEANUP PERSONNEL. column168: THE DRIVER PICKED UP A SHIPMENT OF HAZARDOUS WASTE FROM SEAPORT DOCK IN FOUCHAN, LOUISIANA. THE SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF EIGHT 55 GALLON DRUMS OF NON-HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND ONE 550 GALLON TOTE TANK CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE. THE CONTAINERS WERE LOADED ON THE LAIDLAW TRUCK BY DOCK PERSONNEL. PRIOR TO LOADING, THE DRIVER VISUALLY INSPECTED THE CONTAINERS AND FOUND NO DEFECTS. WHILE ENROUTE TO THE DESTINATION (JUST EAST OF LAKE CHARLES, LOUISIANA), THE DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE TRAILER AND PULLED INTO A TRUCK STOP AT MILE MARKER 36 ON INSTATE 10. THE DRIVER NOTIFIED THE DISPATCHER OF THE SPILL. A CLEAN UP CREW WAS DISPATCHED FROM THE LAIDLAW OFFICE IN LAKE CHARLES, LOUISIANA. THE SPILL MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP, THE TRAILER DECONTAMINATED AND THE LEAKING PORTABLE TANK WAS SEALED. IT IS BELIEVED THAT A BAD GASKET FOUND ON THE TANK LID CREATED AN IMPROPER SEAL. THE VIBRATION OF THE ROAD THEN CAUSED THE LID TO WORK LOOSE AND POP OPEN, CAUSING THE SPILL. THE GASKET WAS PROMPTLY REPLACED AND THE LID WAS SEALED AND TIGHTENED IN PLACE. THE CLEANUP MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN AN APPROPRIATE CONTAINER FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT, LAIDLAW DRIVERS WILL BE INSTRUCTED TO INSPECT THE GASKETS ON PORTABLE TANK LIDS. DRIVERS WILL BE EQUIPPED WITH NEW GASKETS SO THEY CAN REPLACE ANY FAULTY GASKETS FOUND PRIOR TO LOADING.

ON WEDNESDAY, FEBRUARY 25, 1998, OUR DRIVER WAS DELIVERING A SHIPMENT TO THE RED BANK CITY GARAGE. DRIVER MISSED THE ENTRANCE TO THE FACILITY AND WAS FORCED TO DRIVE APPROXIMATELY 1 MILE PAST THE ENTRANCE TO CHANGE DIRECTION. DRIVER ENTERED THE FACILITY - HOWEVER WHEN ENTERING FACILITY FROM THIS DIRECTION, THE TRUCK PASSED OVER A "DIP" IN THE ROAD. THIS "DIP" JARRED SEVERAL CONTAINERS HOLDING THE PRODUCT ABOVE. AS DRIVER BACKED INTO THE BAY DOOR OF THE GARAGE, EMPLOYEES NOTICED A LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE TRUCK. BEING A SMALL SPILL, THE DRIVER AND GARAGE EMPLOYEES MADE A CONTAINMENT BERM OUT OF "OIL-DRY". THIS CONTAINMENT BERM, ALONG WITH THE SECUREMENT OF THE CONTAINERS STOPPED THE FLOW OF THE SPILL. THE REGULATORY DIVISION OF TAYLOR LABORATORIES WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED. ONCE ON THE SCENE, TAYLOR LABORATORIES, INC. EMPLOYEES THOROUGHLY COVERED THE SPILLED LIQUID WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILL. SODIUM BICARBONATE WAS SPRINKLE NOT ONLY ON THE GROUND BUT WAS SPRINKLED ON THE INSIDE OF THE TRUCK, ONTO THE CONTAINERS, AS WELL AS ON THE UNDERSIDE OF THE TRUCK. ONCE THE SPILL WAS NEUTRALIZED,THE "OIL-DRY" AND SODIUM BICARBONATE WAS SWEPT UP AND PLACED IN PLASTIC BAGS (THESE BAGS WERE THEN TAKEN TO TAYLOR LABORATORIES, INC. FOR TREATMENT). THE CONTAINERS IN QUESTION WERE PLACED IN SEALED PLASTIC BAGS FOR TRANSPORT BACK TO TAYLOR LABORATORIES, INC. FOR TREATMENT. ONCE GROUND BELOW THE TRUCK WAS CLEARED, THE TRUCK WAS MOVED APPROXIMATELY 30 FEET AND THE FLOOR OF THE TRUCK WAS GIVEN ANOTHER COAT OF SODIUM BICARBONATE TO ENSURE THAT ANY RESIDUAL ON THE BOTTOMS OF PALLETS IN THE TRUCK WOULD BE COMPLETELY NEUTRALIZED. THE CONTENTS OF THE TRUCK WERE THEN PROPERLY LOADED AND SECURED. ONCE THE TRUCK WAS MOVED, THE GROUND WAS COMPLETELY RE-SWEPT TO ENSURE THAT NO CONTAMINATE REMAINED. CLEAN WATER WAS THEN POURED AROUND THE CONTAINMENT AREA (THIS WOULD SHOW ANY AREAS THAT CONTAINED ANY RESIDUAL SULFURIC ACID - IF THE WATER "BUBBLED" IT INDICATED SOME SULFURIC REMAINED. ANY AREAS THAT SHOWED SIGNS OF RESIDUAL WERE TREATED WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE. THE ENTIRE AREA WAS THEN TREATED WITH PH STRIPS TO ENSURE THAT THE ENTIRE ARE OF  THE SPILL HAD BEEN NEUTRALIZED TO A PH WITHIN A RANGE OF 6-8. ONCE THE AREA WAS CLEAN AND CLEAR, THE TRUCK WAS RETURNED TO TAYLOR LABORATORIES, INC. IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT TWO EMPLOYEES FOLLOWED BEHIND THE TRUCK TO OBSERVE ANY SIGNS OF LEAKAGE WHILE IN ROUTE. ONCE AT TAYLOR LABORATORIES, INC., THE CONTENTS OF THE TRUCK WERE CAREFULLY REMOVED AND BROUGHT INSIDE THE FACILITY FOR CLEAN-UP. THE TRUCK WAS THEN IMMEDIATELY SENT TO A LOCAL CLEAN-UP SHOP FOR PROPER CLEANING INSIDE AND OUT (AS IS REQUIRED BY 49 CFR 177.858, ACCIDENTS INVOLVING CLASS 8, CORROSIVE MATERIALS). IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THE PROPER AUTHORITIES WERE CONTACTED AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT. THE RED BANK FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AND RULED THAT THE STEPS THAT WE WERE TAKING WERE APPROPRIATE. COMMAND OF THE SCENE WAS GIVEN TO DON E. REYNOLDS, VICE PRE
UPON UNLOADING AT THE CONSIGNEE LOCATION A BOX WAS DROPPED CAUSING THE TOP OF 1 GALLON BOTTLE TO OPEN AND SPILL SOME OF THE CONTENTS. IT WAS CLEANED UP WITH FLOOR DRY AND HELD FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

column168: APPROXIMATELY 1:55 PM ON 2/25/98 LACY'S EXPRESS DRIVER DON MATHES WAS TRANSPORTING CONTAINERS OF WASTE TO EAST CHICAGO, IN WHEN HE DISCOVERED SOMETHING LEAKING OUT OF HIS TRAILER. HE PULLED OVER INTO A SAFE CONSTRUCTION AREA OFF THE MAIN ROAD. LACY'S TRAILER WAS LOADED AT SAFETY KLEEN IN WEST CHESTER, PA PRIOR TO BEING ON ROADWAY. ALL CONTAINERS APPEARED TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION. LACY'S DRIVER IMMEDIATELY TELEPHONED LACY'S TERMINAL IN PEDRICKTOWN, NJ TO REPORT LEAKAGE. THE DRIVER WAS TRAVELING PAST LANCASTER, PA ON ROUTE 30 WEST JUST BEFORE WHERE 30 & 283 MEET. LACY'S TRACTORS ARE EQUIPPED WITH CELLULAR TELEPHONES JUST FOR THIS TYPE OF SITUATION. LACY'S TRAILER CONTAINED BOTH HAZARDOUS AND NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE. UNKNOWN WHAT WAS LEAKING AT THAT TIME. LACY'S IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED SAFETY KLEEN. SAFETY KLEEN (TREVOR BAILER) INFORMED LACY'S THAT THEY WOULD RESPOND AND HANDLE THE SITUATION. LACY'S DRIVER ISOLATED THE VEHICLE AND WAITED FOR RESPONSE PERSONNEL. DRIVERS ARE TRAINED NOT TO STOP BY STORM DRAINS OR STREAMS, PULL OVER IN A SAFE AREA AND CONTAIN THE SPILL USING THEIR SPILL CONTROL KIT. SAFETY KLEEN NOTIFIED ALL APPROPRIATE PERSONNEL (FIRE, EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND DEP). IT WAS DETERMINED BY THE SPILL RESPONSE TEAM THAT TWO CONTAINERS WERE LEAKING. THEY WERE OVERPACKED. THE CONTAINERS WERE PICKED UP FROM THE GENERATOR PORTER INSTRUMENTS, 246 TOWNSHIPLINE ROAD, HARTFIELD, PA BY SAFETY KLEEN, TRANSPORT #1. LACY'S EXPRESS PICKED THEM UP AT SAFETY KLEEN IN WEST CHESTER, PA IN ORDER TO TRANSPORT TO EAST CHICAGO, IN. ACCORDING TO THE RESPONSE TEAM THE CONTAINERS APPEARED TO BE GOOD HOWEVER THEY WERE BADLY RUSTED BUT PAINTED OVER SO YOU COULD NOT EASILY DETECT A BAD CONTAINER. ALSO THERE WERE METAL SHAVINGS IN THE CONTAINERS. WHEN TESTED THE MATERIAL WAS ABOUT 98% WATER. JEFF YORTY FROM THE PA DEP WAS ON THE SCENE. WILLIAM GURNEY, GENERAL MANAGER OF LACY'S EXPRESS CONTACTED MR. YORTY CONTACTED MR. YORTY THE FOLLOWING DAY AS A F FOLLOW UP TO SEE IF ANYTHING ELSE WAS NEEDED FROM LACY'S END. MR. YORTY SAID EVERYTHING WENT WELL BUT WAS BLOWN OUT OF PROPORTION BECAUSE OF ALL THE RESPONDERS THAT WERE NOT NEEDED. CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETE BY THE RESPONSE TEAM HMHTTC AND THE DRIVER WAS ON HIS WAY BY 8 PM THAT EVENING. THERE WAS NO FURTHER LEAKAGE. SAFETY KLEEN ACKNOWLEDGED FULL RESPONSIBILITY FOR CLEAN UP COST ETC. THERE WERE NO INJURIES, DAMAGE OR CONTAMINATION. THERE WERE ALSO NO EXPOSURES TO PEOPLE.

column168: BEALINE DRIVER STANLEY RICH DEPARTED BEALINE'S PASADENA TERMINAL AT 5:45 AM IN HIS ASSIGNED TRACTOR, 103 AND PULLING TRAILER 204. HIS INSTRUCTIONS WERE TO LOAD WASTE ORGANIC MATERIAL AT ELF ATOCHEM IN CROSBY, TEXAS AND TRANSPORT TO RHONE POULENC (RHODIA) IN HOUSTON, TEXAS. MR. RICH ARRIVED AT ELF ATOCHEM AT APPROXIMATELY 6:30 AM. LOADING WAS COMPLETED AT APPROXIMATELY 7:05 AM, AND MR. RICH DEPARTED THE FACILITY AT APPROXIMATELY 7:25 AM FOR HIS DESTINATION MR. RICH EXITED ELF ATOCHEM ONTO CROSBY EASTGATE ROAD, AND HAD TRAVELED APPROXIMATELY 1/4 MILE. HE STOPPED AT A RAILROAD CROSSING PARALLEL TO US HIGHWAY 90, AND PROCEEDED THROUGH THE CROSSING. AT THIS POINT MR. RICH STATED  THAT HE LOOKED IN HIS MIRRORS AND NOTICED MATERIAL SPILLING DOWN SIDES OF TRAILER. MR. RICH SAID THAT HE STOPPED HIS TRAILER AND BACKED UP A SHORT DISTANCE TO REDUCE ANGLE OF THE TRAILER. MR RICH CONTACTED BEALINE DISPATCH AT APPROXIMATELY 7:30 AM BY TWO WAY RADIO, AND ASKED THEM TO REQUEST ASSISTANCE FROM ELF ATOCHEM. MR. RICH THEN STATED THAT HE USED A SHOVEL TO DIKE SIDES OF ROAD TO PREVENT ANY MATERIAL FROM ENTERING A DITCH BETWEEN UP RAILROAD TRACKS AND US HIGHWAY 90. DUE TO THE CLOSE PROXIMITY OF THE SPILL SITE TO THE GENERATOR, RESPONSE TOOK ONLY A FEW MINUTES. INITIAL ELF ATOCHEM RESPONDERS ASSESSED SITUATION AND REQUESTED A CLEAN-UP CREW FROM THEIR FACILITY TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE. AFTER NOTIFYING THE GENERATOR, BEALINE DISPATCHER NOTIFIED RICHARD CIRILLO, BEALINE SAFETY DIRECTOR. MR CIRILLO IN TURN CONTACTED BEALINE TECHNICAL REPRESENTATIVE, LESLIE EDWARDS AND BOTH MR. CIRILLO AND MR. EDWARDS RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, MR. EDWARDS WAS DIRECTED TO WORK WITH ELF ATOCHEM PERSONNEL AT THE SPILL SITE. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONFINED TO THE ASPHALT SURFACE OF THE ROAD. ABSORBENT BARRIERS WERE PLACED BY ELF ATOCHEM PERSONNEL AT STRATEGIC LOCATIONS AS A PRECAUTION TO PREVENT ANY MATERIAL FROM REACHING A DITCH BETWEEN THE UP RAILROAD TRACKS AND US HIGHWAY 90. ABSORBENT MATERIAL SUPPLIED BY ELF ATOCHEM (GENERATOR) WAS APPLIED TO THE AREAS WHERE SPILLAGE OCCURRED. SUFFICIENT ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS USED TO ABSORB ALL FREE LIQUIDS. THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN FOUR D.O.T. OVERPACK DRUMS AND RETURNED TO THE GENERATOR FOR  SUBSEQUENT DISPOSAL IN ACCORDANCE WITH APPLICABLE GOVERNMENTAL REGULATIONS. TRAFFIC CONTROL WAS HANDLED BY THE HARRIS COUNTY SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT. AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE, THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD WAS NOTIFIED. THE TRACK WAS REOPENED TO RAILROAD TRAFFIC AT 9:15 AM CROSBY EASTGATE ROAD WAS BLOCKED IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWING INCIDENT TO PREVENT ANY SPREAD OF THE MATERIAL. IN ADDITIONAL THE SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT DETOURED TRAFFIC AROUND ONE LANE OF US HIGHWAY 90 FROM 8:00 AM UNTIL 9:30 AM. AT THAT TIME, ONE LANE OF CROSBY EASTGATE ROAD WAS RE-OPENED TO TRAFFIC. THE SECOND LANE OF CROSBY EASTGATE ROAD WAS RE-OPENED UPON COMPLETION OF CLEAN-UP AT APPROXIMATELY 10:15 AM. THE CROSBY VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND S

INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE TANK CAR WAS EQUIPPED WITH  A TOP OPERATING ROD/HANDLE FOR THE BOTTOM OUTLET. WHILE THE PACKING NUT AT THE TOP OPERATING HANDLE WAS TIGHT, THE OPERATING TAD/HANDLE WAS EASILY TURNED BY HAND A FULL HALF TURN TO TIGHTEN THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  THE ROD WAS FURTHER TIGHTENED UTILIZING A PIPE WRENCH, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. THE GROUND AREA AFFECTED BY THE DRIPPING LIQUID WILL BE ADDRESSED AT THE SAME TIME ADJACENT AREAS FROM A PREVIOUS RELEASE ARE DECONTAMINATED.  DUE TO THE TYPE OF COMMODITY AND THE MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY THE DENVER RMCC REPORTING A SUSPECTED LEAKING TANK CAR AT YERMO, CA.  THE EXACT SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS UNKNOWN AT THE TIME.  THREE CARMEN FROM THE MECHANICAL (CAR) DEPARTMENT HAD BEEN EXPOSED TO AN UNKNOWN VAPOR ODOR AND WERE COMPLAINING OF EYE AND THROAT IRRITATION. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED LARRY HOLT, MANAGER, MECHANICAL (CAR) DEPARTMENT, YERMO WHO STATED 3 MEMBERS OF HIS GROUP HAD BEEN WORKING ON THE WEST END OF YARD TRACK C3 INSPECTING A TRAIN SCHEDULED FOR DEPARTURE, WHEN THEY DETECTED AN UNUSUAL ODOR. WHILE THE ODOR CAUSED SOME IRRITATION, THEY CONTINUED TO WORK THE TRAIN EASTBOUND, AWAY FROM THE INITIAL EXPOSURE AREA. UPON RETURNING TO THE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT OFFICE, THEY REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO MANAGER HOLT.  IT WAS RECOMMENDED MANAGER HOLT HAVE THE INDIVIDUALS TRANSPORTED TO BARSTOW COMMUNITY HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION AND TREATMENT.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY AND MET WITH THE INCIDENT COMMANDER, FIRE CHIEF TOM YATES, YERMO FIRE DEPARTMENT.  CHIEF YATES ADVISED HE REQUESTED ASSISTANCE FROM THE BARSTOW FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM AND THE ADJACENT YERMO ANNEX MARINE CORP FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM.  THE YARD HAD BEEN CLOSED DOWN AND SWITCHING OPERATIONS CURTAILED UNTIL THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR COULD BE INVESTIGATED.  THERE WERE 3 TANK CARS IN THE WEST END OF YARD TRACK #208, WHICH IS ADJACENT TO THE C3 TRACK.  IT WAS SUSPECTED ON OF THE 3 CARS, ONE OF WHICH CONTAINED TOLUENE DIISOCYANATE, MAY HAVE BEEN THE SOURCE OF THE ODORS.  AT THIS POINT THE INCIDENT WAS SCALED BACK, AND MANAGER COOPER, ALONG WITH 2 MEMBERS OF THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZ MAT TEAM, AND 2 MEMBERS FROM SAN BERNARDINO COUNTY HEALTH HAZ MAT, ENTERED THE AREA TO PERFORM A DETAILED CAR INSPECTION.  UPON INSPECTING THE ABOVE TANK CAR, A SLIGHT HISSING NOISE WAS DETECTED, WHICH WAS COMING FROM THE AREA OF THE MANWAY COVER PLATE.  DEVELOPED 2 OF THE 8 SWING BOLTS THAT SECURE THE COVER PLATE WERE LOOSE AND COULD BE TURNED BY HAND.  UPON TIGHTENING THE #3 & #8 BOLTS (CLOCKWISE FROM THE PLATE HINGE), FOUND THAT THE REMAINING SWING BOLTS COULD ALSO BE TURNED BY HAND.  ALL OF THE COVER PLATE SWING BOLTS WERE PROPERLY SECURED, WHICH STOPPED THE ESCAPING VAPOR.  WHILE INSPECTION THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS, OBSERVED THE LIQUID LINE BALL VALVE TO BE CLOSED, HOWEVER THE CLOSURE PLUG WAS LOOSE AND COULD BE TURNED BY HAND.  THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE, AND THE PLUG WAS PROPERLY SECURED.  AT THIS POINT THE INCIDENT WAS TERMINATED. THE 3 EMPLOYEES HAD RETURNED FROM THE HOSPITAL AND COMPLETED THEIR SCHEDULED WORK SHIFTS WITH NO FURTHER INCIDENT. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: ON 2/28/98, A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. THE LOCATION OF THE SPILL WAS IN OUR "A" FACILITY. MITCH AYERS WENT TO FRANKLIN SQUARE HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION AND THEN WENT TO SEE HIS PERSONAL PHYSICIAN. MITCH RECEIVED SOME MEDICATION FOR HIS EYES AND WAS ABLE TO RETURN TO WORK THE NEXT DAY.

AT THIS TIME THE LAIDLAW DRIVER WAS INFORMED THAT THE TANKER #305 (VIN#5431ARCO) WAS SPATTERING FLUIDS AND THAT MATERIAL WAS RECEIVED ONTO THE AUTOMOBILE OF STEVE MORRIS WHILE THE VEHICLES WERE IN MOTION. THE LAIDLAW (FS) DRIVER CONFIRMED THE NATURE OF THE PROBLEM AND ASSESSED THAT THE WING NUTS ON THE FRONT DOME LID HAD BECOME LOOSE DURING TRANSIT AND APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF MATERIAL HAD LEAKED FROM THE DOME LID IN THE CROWS NEST. THIS WAS THE SOURCE OF THE MATERIAL BEING BLOWN IN A FINE MIST FROM THE TOP OF THE TRAILER. THE LAIDLAW (FS) DRIVER IMMEDIATELY ATTEMPTED TO CLEAN THE VEHICLE OF MR. MORRIS WITH ABSORBENT PADS AND MR. MORRIS WAS INFORMED OF THE TRUCK NUMBER AND DRIVERS NAME. MR MORRIS WAS GIVEN A CONTACT NUMBER FOR THE COMPANY AND INFORMED THE DRIVER THAT HE WAS GOING TO A CAR WASH IMMEDIATELY AND WOULD CONTACT THE COMPANY AFTER HIS VEHICLE WAS CLEANED. THE LAIDLAW (FS) DRIVER PROCEEDED TO CLEAN THE MATERIAL FROM THE CROWS NEST AND SIDES OF THE TANKER AND TIGHTENED THE WING NUTS ON THE DOME LID. AT THIS POINT THE DRIVER BELIEVED THAT THE MATERIAL WAS SAFE TO MOVE AND PROCEEDED TO A PHONE. THE DRIVER CONTACTED SAN ANTONIO AT 12:30 P.M. AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT. THE DRIVER INDICATED THAT THE TANKER WAS OPERATIONAL AND HE WOULD PROCEED TO SAN ANTONIO, MAKING FREQUENT STOPS TO CHECK THE DOME LID WING NUTS. COMPLETION OF THIS DELIVERY WAS MADE TO LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (SAN ANTONIO), INC. WITH NO FURTHER LOSS OF MATERIAL. UPON RECEIPT AT THE FACILITY TANKER 305 WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE (FEBRUARY 25, 1998). THE TANKER WAS SENT FRUEHAUF TRAILER OPERATIONS, INC. FOR MECHANICAL EVALUATION AND RE-CERTIFICATION ON MARCH 2ND DURING RE-CERTIFICATION THE FRUEHAUL'S STAFF WAS CONSULTED ON THE SUSPECT DOME LID'S MECHANICAL INTEGRITY AND WAS ASKED TO GIVE OPINIONS ON THE EFFECTIVENESS OF A THREE WING NUT SECURING SYSTEM (REFERENCE PHOTOS 1-4) FRUEHAUF INDICATED THAT THE FASTENING SYSTEM WAS ADEQUATE TO PROVIDE A SECURE AND TIGHT SEAL OF THE DOME GASKET TO THE TANKER. FRUEHAUF COULD NOT DETECT ANY PROBLEMS WITH THE FRONT DOME LID OR GASKET ON TANKER 305 NOR COULD THEY DEVELOP ANY THEORIES THAT WOULD SUBSTANTIATE THE ABILITY OF THE WING NUTS TO BECOME LOOSE IF PROPERLY SECURED. TANKER 305 WAS RE-CERTIFIED ON MARCH 6TH AND RELEASED TO SERVICE ON MARCH 9TH . THE LAIDLAW (FS) DRIVER MADE A STATEMENT REFLECTING THAT THE DOME LIDS WERE SECURED BEFORE DEPARTING THE SHIPPERS SITE. IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE DRIVER MADE AN EFFORT TO TIGHTEN THE WING NUTS BUT FAILED TO COMPLETELY SECURE THEM. LAIDLAW DOES NOT BELIEVE THIS INCID
USING DECISION TREE TO CORROSIVE PH OF 6.  AND CLAY ABSORBENT PROCESSED THROUGH DMP, DECONTAMINATED PPE.
